24. Common Pitfalls to Avoid
Architecture Pitfalls
❌ Skipping tenant isolation on even ONE endpoint
   → Any query without organizationId = data leak between tenants

❌ Publishing events OUTSIDE the DB transaction
   → App crash between commit and publish = lost events
   → Always use transactional outbox pattern

❌ Storing raw tokens in DB
   → Always store SHA-256 hash only
   → Raw token only travels in HTTP response, never persisted

❌ Hardcoding secrets in source code
   → Use env vars, validate at startup, mask in logs

❌ Building modules out of order
   → Auth before IAM = circular dependency hell
   → Follow the build order in Section 21

❌ Skipping idempotency on mutations
   → Network retry = duplicate invoice/charge/email
   → Always accept and check idempotencyKey

❌ Using Float for money
   → Float arithmetic errors: 0.1 + 0.2 = 0.30000000000000004
   → Always use Decimal(19,4)


Copy

Insert at cursor
Security Pitfalls
❌ Logging request bodies
   → Bodies may contain passwords, tokens, card numbers
   → Log only method + path + status + duration

❌ Returning stack traces in production
   → Exposes internal structure to attackers
   → Return generic message in prod, full error in dev only

❌ Trusting client-provided organizationId
   → Always read organizationId from JWT, never from request body

❌ Skipping email verification
   → Allows anyone to register with someone else's email
   → Always verify before granting access

❌ Not revoking sessions on password reset
   → Attacker who stole session keeps access after password change
   → Always revoke ALL refresh tokens on password reset

❌ Weak JWT secrets
   → Short secrets = brute-forceable
   → Minimum 64 hex chars (256 bits) for both access + refresh secrets

